hin the village. Hesiod's Ascra directly counters the accepted view of Works and Days, which has Hesiod describing a peasant society subordinated to the economic and political control of an outside elite. Through his deft analysis, Edwards suggests a new understanding of both Works and Days and the social and economic organization of Hesiod's time and place.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAgriculture in literature. 0aDidactic poetry, GreekxHistory and criticism. 0aFarm life in literature. 0aFarmerszGreecevBiography. 0aPoets, GreekvBiography. 0aVillages in literature. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aagriculture.  aancient greece.  aancient history.  aaristocracy.  aboeotia.  aclassical history.  aclassicism.  aclassics.  acommunity.  acultural studies.  adays.  adebt.  adidactic poetry.  afamily life.  afamily structure.  afarmers.  afarming.  agreece.  agreek culture.  agreek democracy.  agreek poetry.  ahamlet.  ahellenism.  ahesiod.  ainheritance.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary.  aliterature.  amorality.  anonfiction.  anorthern greece.  apeasants.  aperses.  apoems.  apoetry.  apoverty.  aproperty.  arural.  asacra.  aself.  asocial history.  avillage.  awealth.  aworks.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023658540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092957940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520929579423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520929579/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY